metadata.name: Traveler #12
metadata.description:
Retro sci-fi style landscape sketch drawn by code.

Features:
- Terrain: Cliff, Cavern, Sky, Megalopolis, Desert, Sea, Space, Volcano
- Orientation: Landscape, Portlait
- Palette: White, Cream, Tan, Pink, Green, Yellow, Orange
- Background: Light, Dark

Live view options:
- Press "s" key: Saves the high resolution image (4200 x 3300 for landscape, 3300 x 4200 for portlait)

Depending on the device you run it on, it may take some time for the drawing to complete.
Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Sprocket Factory #189
metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

"A Doodle, Ringer, and Fidenza walk into a Space Bar..."

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "P" to export an PNG raster image (10k resolution.)
- Press "S" to export an SVG vector.

metadata.name: Botanical Ghosts #304
metadata.description:
This is a work about growth, impermanence and decay. Ghostly plants and flowers grow around an invisible point, but they immediately begin to fade into the dark background and are soon replaced and covered by others. This process of accumulation and disappearance builds an ever-changing floral garland, or perhaps a funeral wreath.

The monochrome vegetation is part of a fictional flora, born out of random algorithmic combinations, and does not intend to reproduce any real species. It belongs to an “artificial nature” which, like so many worlds that the computers generate for us in movies, games, and virtual reality environments, is a convincing simulation of life, but it is not actually living. AI bots, virtual assistants and non-player characters are also representatives of the uncanny realm of the not-really-alive-but-looking-like-it, which are becoming an increasingly relevant presence in our everyday lives.

These plants and flowers speak about life as a process of incessant renovation, but also about death as the background that’s always there and makes life possible. This spectral vegetation seems to thrive precisely at the verge between both worlds.
_______________


This work is animated and will adapt to any screen size. It generates a never-ending ring of algorithmic foliage, which never repeats itself, and is different for each token. The image preview is triggered after the first five plants or flowers.
Made with p5.js

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture

metadata.name: Everything flows #2
metadata.description:
The Generative Token is obtained in two stages: in the first stage warped noise is generated using the method explained by Inigo Quilez (see Licence.txt for reference); in the second stage, using Sobel method for edge detection, the noise gradient orientation is used to generate flow lines.

The first stage generate an image colored using the values of warped noise.
The second stage generate another image using gradient orientations both for shapes (the flow lines) and for coloring.
The two images are blended together to obtain the final result.

In both stages the color-maps are generated using a sinusoidal function of the gradient orientation angle with a random phases. There are 52 possible combinations of random phases.
Some palette used in the second stage are re-mixed using simplex noise with 20% of probability.

The user can save a 1200x1200 png with 's'.

Sources of variations are:
- Four noise warping control parameters generating different grade of complexity and different shape (combined on a single number on the features)
- 52 generated color mapping for warped noise
- 52 generated color mapping for flow lines
- Blending of the two intermediate images

Features:
Grays: 25% of probability to have a grays palette, (True, False)
Color Palette: one of the 52 possible combinations of random phases
Color Mixing: 20% of probability to have a re-mixed palette
Noise Control: noise control parameter, (0 - 15)
Rare: when Grays = True and Noise Control < 4
